ited Kingdom","Hamesfield, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thornborough","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of various places, including Thornborough in Allerton Mauleverer (WR Yorks), Thornbrough in South Kilvington (NR Yorks), Thornbrough in Corbridge (Northumb), and Thornborough (Bucks).  See also  Thornbury   and   Thornber  .","2  Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’;  compare  Thornton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornborrow","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."]},{"name":"Thornburrow","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Thornberry  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornberry","meanings":["English (southwestern): habitational name from any of various places called Thornbury, in particular Thornbury (Gloucestershire), Thornbury (Herefordshire), or perhaps Thornbury (Devon), or Thornbury in Bradford (Yorkshire). These placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’ or ‘manor’.","English: variant of   Thornber  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornbery","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornburgh","meanings":["English (Worcestershire) and Irish: variant of   Thornbury  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Rowland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William  Rowland Thornborough was born in 1430, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Thornburgh, was 20 and his mother, Lady Eleanor MUsgrave, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Middleton. He died in 1444, in his hometown, at the age of 14."},"et":{"1430–1444":"1430–1444","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1440–1525":"1440–1525","1410–1491":"1410–1491","1411–1493":"1411–1493","1525":"1525","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","1493":"1493","1491":"1491","1429":"1429","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hamesfield, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–1444":"1430–1444","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1440–1525":"1440–1525","1410–1491":"1410–1491","1411–1493":"1411–1493","1525":"1525","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","1493":"1493","1491":"1491","1429":"1429","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hamesfield, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–1444":"1430–1444","1395–Female":"1395–Décédée","1440–1525":"1440–1525","1410–1491":"1410–1491","1411–1493":"1411–1493","1525":"1525","1444":"1444","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","14